answer:
If $x = \angle BAC,$ then $\angle ABC = \angle ACB = 90^\circ - \frac{x}{2}.$  Also, $\angle BDC = 180^\circ - \angle BDC - \angle CBD - \angle CDB = 180^\circ - (90^\circ - x) - 2(90^\circ - \frac{x}{2}) = 3x.$ Thus, we must have $3x = 3 \angle BAC,$ which means that $\angle BAC = 30^\circ.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

Then $AB = AC = \frac{AM}{\sin 30^\circ} = 22.$  The perimeter of $\triangle ABC$ is $2AB + BC = 22 + 22 + 11\sqrt{3} = \boxed{44 + 11\sqrt{3}}.$

